  "prompt": "When and how did Gautama Buddha die?",
  "response": "Gautama Buddha, the founder of Buddhism, is believed to have died around 483 BCE, though some sources suggest dates as early as 543 BCE or as late as 400 BCE. His death is referred to as his **Parinirvana**, which signifies his final release from the cycle of death and rebirth (samsara).\n\n### How He Died:\nAccording to Buddhist tradition, Buddha died in **Kushinagar** (in present-day Uttar Pradesh, India) at the age of 80. He fell ill after consuming a meal offered by a blacksmith named **Cunda**. The meal is said to have included a dish called *sukaramaddava*, which has been interpreted in various ways (possibly pork or a type of mushroom). Buddha instructed Cunda not to feel guilty, as the meal was one of his most meritorious offerings.\n\nAfter eating, Buddha experienced severe dysentery but continued his journey to Kushinagar. There, he lay down between two sal trees and delivered his final teachings to his disciples. He emphasized the importance of diligence, mindfulness, and his teachings (the Dharma) as their guide after his passing. With his last words, he is said to have declared, *\"All conditioned things are impermanent. Strive on with diligence.\"*\n\n### Significance:\nBuddha's Parinirvana is a pivotal event in Buddhism. It marks the end of his physical presence but also reinforces the core Buddhist teachings of impermanence (anicca), the cessation of suffering, and the attainment of Nirvana. The site of his death, Kushinagar, remains a major pilgrimage site for Buddhists.\n\nBuddha's relics were distributed and enshrined in stupas across the region, becoming centers of veneration. His death is commemorated annually in many Buddhist traditions as **Parinirvana Day**.",
